12. Glossary for Beginners
Kerberos – Network authentication protocol used by Active Directory.
AS-REP – Authentication Service Response; sent by the Domain Controller when a user requests a ticket.
Pre-authentication – A security measure where the client proves knowledge of the password before getting a ticket.
AS-REP Roasting – An attack that requests AS-REP messages for users with pre-authentication disabled, then cracks the encrypted data offline.
SMB – Server Message Block, a protocol for file sharing on Windows networks.
WinRM – Windows Remote Management, allows remote command execution (like SSH on Linux).
DCSync – An attack that uses Directory Replication Service to request password hashes from a Domain Controller.
Pass-the-Hash – Using only the NTLM hash (not the plaintext password) to authenticate to Windows services.
RID Brute Force – Guessing user IDs (Relative Identifiers) to discover domain users.
CrackMapExec – A Swiss‑army knife for attacking Active Directory environments.

